<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF206-952-386  </DOCNO><DOCID>06 952 386  OV: 06 950 660.andM; </DOCID><JOURNAL>PC Magazine  Feb 14 1989 v8 n3 p268(2)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Z-Nix Super Hi-Res Mouse. (Hardware Review) (one of 17 evaluationsof mouse devices) (evaluation)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Stanton, Tom.andM;</AUTHOR><SUMMARY>The Z-Nix Super Hi-Res Mouse, distributed by IMSI, is a $95, 340dpi resolution mouse that is unremarkable in design and execution.andO;Its tear-drop shaped body has three buttons.andP;  The far-left buttonis shorter than the rest; unfortunately, it is also the mostfrequently used button, requiring the user to stretch to reach it.andO;The mouse's Microsoft emulation is very good, and it is accuratein tight drawing tests, but poorly documented and incompletesoftware and sluggish response make this less than a top choice.andM;</SUMMARY><DESCRIPT>Company:   Z-Nix (products).andO;Product:   Z-Nix Super Hi-Res Mouse (Cursor control device).andO;Topic:     MiceI-O DevicesCursor Control DevicesEvaluation.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Z-Nix Super Hi-Res Mouse Often when a product is named &quot;super,&quot; it sets youup for a disappointment.andP;  Unfortunately, Z-Nix's $95 Super Hi-Res Mouse isjust such a product.andP;  It is unremarkable in design and execution, and I foundit to be one of the least responsive mice of all we tested.andM;The Super Hi-Res mimics Microsoft's older teardrop-shaped body, but adds atwist: instead of two buttons, it has three.andP;  The far-left button is shorterthan the rest, which I suppose makes it easier to find, but it also meansthat you need to stretch to get at the most frequently used button.andM;Even with 340-dot-per-inch resolution, the Super Hi-Res Mouse felt sluggish,even sticky at times, as though the ball or rollers were catching onsomething.andP;  I inspected everything and found nothing sticking, but thefeeling persisted on a variety of surfaces.andP;  A mouse pad helps, and Z-Nixshould include one or improve its mouse's mechanism.andM;Menu software exists but is not really documented.andP;  The Lotus 1-2-3 menu Itested was obviously not a finished product--a fact underscored by referencesto what an OEM could do with the menu software.andP;  Z-Nix should either perfectthe included menus or eliminate them from the package altogether.andM;The Super Hi-Res Mouse does shine in Microsoft emulation, and it is accuratein tight drawing tests.andP;  Nonetheless, this product lacks the polish in bothdesign and execution to be a top contender.andO;</TEXT></DOC>